text=:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema%0a:Expansion: Alternate interpretation of "Light"%0a:Author: abbyl%0a:Original: [[Articles.PhilosophyLessonsFromLIGHT|PhilosophyLessonsFromLIGHT]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sebastiang|sebastiang]]%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 27.03.2021 - 07:49%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210405-201008-540820#%0a* [-05.04.2021 - 13:10-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210405-201008-540820#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAn alternate way to consider how the word "light" reflects Nacireman society is that the Nacirema people seem to have a strong aversion to having any sort of weight. The phrase "light with bliss" is a compliment and suggests that there is a correlation between being happy and having less weight. Similarly, people are told to "lighten up", implying that Naciremans are focused on losing weight and see extra weight as a bad trait. Even the phrase "bringing to light" can be interpreted as making a thought figuratively lighter so it floats to the front of a person's mind. Given that the Nacirema are so obsessed with losing weight, you probably shouldn't bring food when you visit them for fear of having it confiscated.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
