diff:1616856581:1616856581:=1,38d0%0a%3c :Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema%0a%3c :Expansion: Alternate interpretation of "Light"%0a%3c :Author: abbyl%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.PhilosophyLessonsFromLIGHT|PhilosophyLessonsFromLIGHT]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sebastiang|sebastiang]]%0a%3c :Section: B%0a%3c :Completed: 27.03.2021 - 07:49%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c An alternate way to consider how the word "light" reflects Nacireman society is that the Nacirema people seem to have a strong aversion to having any sort of weight. The phrase "light with bliss" is a compliment and suggests that there is a correlation between being happy and having less weight. Similarly, people are told to "lighten up", implying that Naciremans are focused on losing weight and see extra weight as a bad trait. Even the phrase "bringing to light" can be interpreted as making a thought figuratively lighter so it floats to the front of a person's mind. Given that the Nacirema are so obsessed with losing weight, you probably shouldn't bring food when you visit them for fear of having it confiscated.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
